                     'Achievements','Average playtime forever','Average playtime two weeks','Developers','Publishers','Categories','Genres','Tags']
game_data = df[variables_to_keep]

future_dates = game_data.loc[future_games]

# Number of games released by month
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

plt.ylabel('Number of games')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Price Analysis¶

A majority (95%) of games are priced between 0 and 20. 19% of all games are free on Steam.

There is one game priced at nearly 1000. We'll be removing this outlier.

Only 65 games are priced over 150. We'll be removing these.

In [15]:
bins = range(0, 121, 20)

# Categorizing price into bins
game_data['Price Bin'] = pd.cut(game_data['Price'], bins=bins, right=False, include_lowest=True)

# Count the number of games in each price bin
price_distribution = game_data['Price Bin'].value_counts(normalize=True).sort_index()
print(price_distribution)

DLC analysis¶

Majority of games never add any DLCs

It is a tiny percentage that have 2 or more DLCs.

Surprisingly, the highest DLC count was 2366.

In [19]:
# Number of DLCs (up to 10)
dlc_counts = game_data['DLC count'].value_counts().sort_index()
dlc_counts = dlc_counts[dlc_counts.index <= 10]
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
dlc_counts.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Distribution of the number of DLCs')
plt.xlabel('Number of DLCs')
plt.ylabel('Number of games')
plt.show()

Platform¶

To no suprise, windows dominates the market as the most used operating system.

In [21]:
# What platform do gamers game on?

platform_sums = game_data[['Windows', 'Mac', 'Linux']].sum()

platform_sums.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Number of games available on each platform')

Languages Analysis¶

Majority of games are in English. That applies for both text and audio.

In [22]:
import ast

#This function will convert strings into actual Python object it represents -- here I need strings to lists
def parse_languages(languages_str):
    try:
        return ast.literal_eval(languages_str)
    except Exception as e:
        # Print the problematic string and the error for debugging
        print(f"Error parsing: {languages_str}")
        print(f"Error: {e}")
        return []  # Return an empty list in case of an error
In [23]:
# Apply this function to each row in the 'supported_languages' column
game_data['Supported languages'] = game_data['Supported languages'].apply(parse_languages)

# Flatten the list of supported languages
all_languages = [lang for sublist in game_data['Supported languages'] for lang in sublist]

# Count occurrences of each language
language_counts = Counter(all_languages)

# dictionary into dataframe to easily visualize
lang_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(language_counts, orient='index', columns=['Count'])
lang_df.sort_values('Count', ascending=False, inplace=True)

Review Analysis¶

One-fourth of all games do not have any reviews. These serve as useless.

In [25]:
# Proportion of games with no reviews
round(game_data[(game_data['Positive'] + game_data['Negative']) == 0].shape[0] / game_data.shape[0], 2)
Out[25]:
0.25

Estimated Owners / Units Sold¶

I will remove games with 0 - 0 estimated owners. That means nobody bought the game.

Most games fall had between 0 - 20 estimated owners.

In [26]:
# Estimated owners distribution
game_data['Estimated owners'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar')
Out[26]:
<Axes: xlabel='Estimated owners'>

Playtime¶

A big majority of players play on average under 2000 minutes of playtime alltime for a game.

In the first two weeks, on average most play under 200 minutes.

82% of games have 0 playtime

In [27]:
# Average playtime
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)


plt.hist(game_data['Average playtime forever'], bins=15000, color='blue', alpha=0.7)
plt.title('Total playtime')
plt.xlabel('Playtime (minutes)')
plt.ylabel('Number of games')
plt.xlim(0, 100)
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

plt.hist(game_data['Average playtime two weeks'], bins=32000, color='black', alpha=0.7)
plt.title('Playtime in the last 2 weeks')
plt.xlabel('Playtime (minutes)')
plt.ylabel('Number of games')
plt.xlim(0, 5)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Categories, Genres, Tags Analysis¶

Single-player category is the most popular game. A lot of games also have Steam Achievements

Indie, Casual, and Action are most popular genres.

Indie, Singleplayer, and Action are most popular tags. Tags are what gamers categorize games.

In [30]:
#Splitting categories on the commas since categories is comma-separated string
if isinstance(game_data['Categories'].iloc[0], str):
    game_data['Categories'] = game_data['Categories'].dropna().apply(lambda x: x.split(','))

# Flatten the list of categories
categories = [category.strip() for sublist in game_data['Categories'].dropna() for category in sublist]

# Count occurrences
category_counts = Counter(categories)

# Prepare data for plotting
top_categories = pd.DataFrame(category_counts.most_common(10), columns=['Category', 'Games'])

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
plt.barh(top_categories['Category'], top_categories['Games'])
plt.title('Top 10 Categories by Number of Games')
plt.xlabel('Number of Games')
plt.ylabel('Category')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
plt.show()

In [34]:
import re

# Convert to list if necessary and not already handled
if isinstance(game_data['Developers'].iloc[0], str):
    game_data['Developers'] = game_data['Developers'].dropna().apply(lambda x: x.split(','))

# Regex pattern to remove legal business terms
pattern = r'\b(Inc|LLC|Ltd|LTD|Corp|GmbH|S\.A\.|S\.L\.|Corporation)\b\.?'

# Flatten the list of developers and remove common terms
developers = []
for sublist in game_data['Developers'].dropna():
    for dev in sublist:
        # Clean the developer name by removing legal terms using regex
        cleaned_dev = re.sub(pattern, '', dev).strip()
        developers.append(cleaned_dev)

# Count occurrences
developer_counts = Counter(developers)

# Prepare data for plotting
top_developers = pd.DataFrame(developer_counts.most_common()[1:11], columns=['Developer', 'Games'])

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.barh(top_developers['Developer'], top_developers['Games'])
plt.title('Top 10 Developers by Number of Games')
plt.xlabel('Number of Games')
plt.ylabel('Developer')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.show()

Data Transformation - Cleaning¶

In [42]:
# Make a copy of dateframe
new_game_data = game_data.copy()
In [43]:
#Removing games with no estimated owners
new_game_data = new_game_data[(new_game_data['Estimated owners'] != "0 - 0")]
In [44]:
# Games released before 2010 were very few. 

new_game_data['Release date'] = pd.to_datetime(new_game_data['Release date'], format='mixed')
new_game_data = new_game_data[(new_game_data['Release date'].dt.year >= 2010)]
In [45]:
#remove future dated game
new_game_data = new_game_data[new_game_data['AppID'] != 2022640]
In [46]:
# Remove priced above 150$
new_game_data = new_game_data[(new_game_data['Price'] < 150)]
In [47]:
#Removing Zero reviewed games since it doesnt tell us much
new_game_data = new_game_data[(new_game_data['Positive'] + new_game_data['Negative'] != 0)]
In [48]:
#If game does not have categories then it serves little value
new_game_data = new_game_data[(new_game_data['Categories'].str.len() != 0)]
new_game_data = new_game_data.dropna(subset=['Categories'])

# Calculate the every occurence of tags, supported languages, genres, and categories for each title
df2['tag_count'] = df2['Tags'].apply(lambda x: len(x) if isinstance(x, list) else 0)
df2['Language_count'] = df2['Supported languages'].apply(lambda x: len(x) if isinstance(x, list) else 0)
df2['Genre_count'] = df2['Genres'].apply(lambda x: len(x) if isinstance(x, list) else 0)
df2['Category_count'] = df2['Categories'].apply(lambda x: len(x) if isinstance(x, list) else 0)

In [54]:
# Explode 'Tags' and keep 'tag_count' aligned with each tag
tags_df = df2[['AppID', 'Tags', 'tag_count']].explode('Tags')
tags_df = tags_df.rename(columns={'Tags': 'Tag'})

# Explode 'Categories'
categories_df = df2[['AppID', 'Categories','Category_count']].explode('Categories')
categories_df = categories_df.rename(columns={'Categories': 'Category'})

# Explode 'Genres'
genres_df = df2[['AppID', 'Genres','Genre_count']].explode('Genres')
genres_df = genres_df.rename(columns={'Genres': 'Genre'})

# Explode 'Supported languages' and keep 'Language_count' aligned with each tag
languages_df = df2[['AppID', 'Supported languages','Language_count']].explode('Supported languages')
languages_df = languages_df.rename(columns={'Supported languages': 'Supported language'})

# Remove the list columns from the main DataFrame
notwanted = ['Categories', 'Tags', 'tag_count', 'Supported languages','Language_count','Genres','Genre_count','Categories','Category_count']
final_data = df2.drop(columns=notwanted)
